{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3a9e602e-f2ee-4fb5-af7f-2a0422ec27db","content":"## Recommended: `dotnet-trace`\n\nIt's the easiest purpose-built tool for .NET CPU profiling. No install beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Steps\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds example)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper OS-level + .NET analysis (ETW-based) |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick real-time check before tracing (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) |\n| **WPR/WPA** | Full Windows system-wide kernel + user tracing |\n\n**Tip:** Run `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first — it'll quickly show if CPU is spent in GC, JIT, or user code, helping you target your trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"22080346-6b8c-451b-ba54-02a7a3aa7ea3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":368,"requestId":"204F:1612ED:3A5745:4441DB:69F00CD5"},"id":"f9b13f43-d771-43dc-bbbb-a4e4cf2fd388","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:26:54.890Z","parentId":"8bd70182-0367-4fd7-957e-87a8a46d29a2"}
